    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-10-04T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-10-04T11:00:00-05:00" n="729"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860H.00/10–448: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reams</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-10-04T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 4, 1948—5 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1327. I agree that if Tito should enter war on Soviet side he would almost
                    certainly attempt exclude Soviet troops from Yugoslavia (<gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 565, October 1). However, this would not
                    remove him from dilemma horns. We would feel no more kindly toward him and
                    Russians if victorious would certainly be strong enough remove him. Also agree
                    Russians would prefer liquidate Yugoslav situation before embarking war. They
                    are unlikely succeed if we give him economic support present regime. Odds favor
                    continuation regime even in event Tito assassination. Soviet invasion to enforce
                    change unlikely but should certainly call for immediate positive action our
                    part. I feel strongly that importance maintaining independent defiant Yugoslavia
                    cannot be overestimated. Believe that pull on other satellites may well become
                    irresistible if time permits Tito fully consolidate his position.</p>
                <pb facs="1134" n="1113" xml:id="pg_1113"/>
                <p>Defense must, of course, estimate advantages Yugoslav neutrality. I am inclined
                    believe that it would be possible persuade Tito remain neutral if we so desired.
                    Personally believe this desirable. However, <gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 1303, September 27, based solely on possibility defense
                    might consider desirable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reams</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
